# Fetch Azure/Entra AD Users via PowerShell

We will create a Python package `ADAdmin` capable of fetching all users with detailed attributes including Manager, Licenses, and Groups from Azure/Entra AD using PowerShell under the hood.

## User Review Required
> [!IMPORTANT]  
> The PowerShell script relies on the **Microsoft.Graph** PowerShell module being installed on the system (specifically `Microsoft.Graph.Users` and `Microsoft.Graph.Groups`). It also requires that the user is either already connected via `Connect-MgGraph` or uses an App Registration (Client ID / Tenant ID). The script will assume `Connect-MgGraph` with interactive login if no explicit credentials are provided. Please let me know if you want to use a specific authentication method (like App Registration Secret/Certificate) instead!

## Proposed Changes
### ADAdmin Package
#### [NEW] [client.py](file:///y:/WinToolbox/ADAdmin/client.py)
Creates the `ADClient` class that acts as a wrapper for executing PowerShell queries and parsing the JSON output back to Python dictionaries.

#### [NEW] [scripts/get_all_users.ps1](file:///y:/WinToolbox/ADAdmin/scripts/get_all_users.ps1)
A PowerShell script utilizing the Microsoft Graph PowerShell module (`Get-MgUser`) to connect, fetch all users with requested properties (`-Property "Id,DisplayName,..."`), expand relationships (`-ExpandProperty Manager`), and extract `MemberOf` and `AssignedLicenses`. Converts results to JSON for the Python client.

#### [MODIFY] [\_\_init\_\_.py](file:///y:/WinToolbox/ADAdmin/__init__.py)
Exposes the `ADClient` for easy importing: `from ADAdmin import ADClient`.

## Verification Plan
### Automated Tests
- Since this relies on an active Active Directory tenant and Graph API permissions (`User.Read.All`, `Directory.Read.All`), automated testing from my side is limited without live credentials. 

### Manual Verification
- You can import the package locally in Python, initiate the client, and call the `get_all_users()` method to verify the output matches expectations.
- We will create a `test.py` script for you to run and verify it directly.
